B.Ls=new A.cq("Grade 3+","Many potentials firing simultaneously in all sampled areas.")
B.Lu=new A.cq("Grade 4+","A full 'interference pattern' of spontaneous activity. The screen is completely obliterated by denervation.")
B.Yp=s([B.LF,B.LK,B.LA,B.Ls,B.Lu],t.LK)
B.a9r=new A.k_("Grade 3+ Positive Sharp Waves","When denervation is severe, you don't just see a few blips. You see abundant positive sharp waves filling the screen across multiple muscle areas. This signifies a structurally significant nerve injury.","fT6Lx4rnRNs",B.Yp)
B.LD=new A.cq("The Sound","An incredibly distinctive, perfectly regular 'machine-like' or 'idling motorcycle' sound.")
B.LN=new A.cq("The Look","Multi-serrated, complex spikes that are completely uniform from discharge to discharge.")
B.LR=new A.cq("The Rate","Typically 5-100Hz. The key is that they are *perfectly* regular, unlike fibs which are semi-rhythmic.")
B.Lx=new A.cq("The Mechanism","Ephaptic transmission. One denervated fiber acts as a pacemaker, triggering adjacent denervated fibers in a closed loop.")
B.Yc=s([B.LD,B.LN,B.LR,B.Lx],t.LK)
B.a9t=new A.k_("Complex Repetitive Discharges (CRDs)","These sound exactly like a perfectly tuned engine. What you're seeing are individual muscle fibers that are time-linked, firing in an ephaptic loop. We see this in chronic, long-standing neuropathic or myopathic conditions.","UE-UIRDzZ-U",B.Yc)
B.LQ=new A.cq("The Sound","A rhythmic, rhythmic bursting. 'Marching soldiers' hitting the pavement.")
B.LZ=new A.cq("The Look","Grouped, repetitive discharges of the exact same Motor Unit Action Potential (MUAP).")
B.Lw=new A.cq("The Rate","Interburst frequency is 1-5Hz; intraburst frequency is 5-60Hz.")
B.Lq=new A.cq("Key Associations","Radiation plexopathy (very common), Multiple Sclerosis (if facial), Guillain-Barr\xe9, or chronic compressive neuropathy.")
B.a_3=s([B.LQ,B.LZ,B.Lw,B.Lq],t.LK)
B.a9w=new A.k_("Myokymic Discharges","Think of an entire motor unit bursting repetitively. It has a very distinct 'marching soldiers' cadence. If you see this in the limbs, strongly consider radiation injury. If you see it in the face, consider MS or a brainstem glioma.","ZClcikXOOaU",B.a_3)
B.LW=new A.cq("The Sound","A 'dive bomber' or a 'revving motorcycle engine'.")
B.LI=new A.cq("The Look","Spiky waves that smoothly grow and then shrink in amplitude while the firing rate speeds up and slows down.")
B.LJ=new A.cq("The Rate","Typically 20-150Hz. Remember, the rate actively changes.")
B.LO=new A.cq("Key Pathology","Myotonic dystrophy, myotonia congenita, paramyotonia congenita, and occasionally hyperkalemic periodic paralysis.")
B.YT=s([B.LW,B.LI,B.LJ,B.LO],t.LK)
B.a9s=new A.k_("Myotonic Discharges","The classic 'dive bomber.' This is an unstable muscle fiber membrane that repetitively discharges. The defining feature is that it waxes and wanes in both frequency and amplitude.","X29z-QTi0tM",B.YT)
B.LT=new A.cq("The Sound","Random, large, distant 'pops'. Think of 'corn popping' slowly in a microwave.")
B.LX=new A.cq("The Look","A normal-looking (or reinnervated) MUAP that fires spontaneously.")
B.LP=new A.cq("The Rate","Very slow and highly irregular (0.1-10Hz).")
B.Lt=new A.cq("Significance","Hallmark of motor neuron irritability (ALS). However, isolated fasciculations in normal muscle are often benign (caffeine, stress, exercise).")
