B.a76=new A.hB("Abductor Pollicis Brevis","Median Nerve, Medial Cord, Anterior Division, Lower Trunk, C8, T1","From the palmar retinaculum, the tubercle of the scaphoid, and the tubercle of the trapezium.","Lateral side of the base of the proximal phalanx of the thumb.","Place the patient's hand resting comfortably in full supination (palm up).","Find the midpoint of a line drawn between the volar aspect of the first metacarpophalangeal joint and the carpometacarpal joint. Insert the needle to a shallow depth of one-quarter to one-half inch.","Ask the patient to palmarly abduct their thumb, pointing it straight up toward the ceiling against your resistance.","If you insert the needle electrode too deeply, you will overshoot the superficial APB and inadvertently sample the deeper opponens pollicis muscle.","This muscle is the quintessential recording site for median nerve motor conduction studies. It will show abnormalities in virtually all median nerve entrapment syndromes, most notably severe Carpal Tunnel Syndrome, with the sole exception being Anterior Interosseous Nerve syndrome. It is also a classic indicator for Klumpke's palsy involving the C8 and T1 roots.","assets/images/emg/Abductor Pollicus Brevis.png")
B.a7a=new A.hB("Biceps Brachii","Musculocutaneous Nerve, Lateral Cord, Anterior Division, Upper Trunk, C5, C6","Long Head originates from the supraglenoid tuberosity of the scapula. Short Head originates from the apex of the coracoid process.","The bicipital tuberosity of the radius.","Have the patient lie supine with their arm resting extended at their side.","Insert the needle directly into the main bulk of the muscle belly in the mid-arm.","Instruct the patient to flex their elbow or forcefully supinate their forearm against resistance.","If the needle electrode is driven too deeply through the biceps belly, it will enter the underlying brachialis muscle.","The biceps serves a powerful dual function: it is both a strong elbow flexor and a primary supinator of the forearm. It is the go-to muscle for evaluating high cervical radiculopathies (C5, C6) and upper trunk brachial plexopathies. In infants, traction injuries during difficult deliveries can stretch these upper roots, leading to the classic 'waiter's tip' posture of Erb-Duchenne palsy.","assets/images/emg/Biceps.png")
B.a70=new A.hB("Extensor Indicis Proprius","Posterior Interosseous Nerve, Radial Nerve, Posterior Cord, Posterior Division, Middle and Lower Trunk, C7, C8","The dorsal surface of the lower half of the ulnar shaft, just below the origin of the extensor pollicis longus.","It joins the ulnar side of the extensor digitorum communis tendon destined for the index finger, terminating in the extensor expansion.","Rest the patient's forearm on the table, fully pronated.","Measure exactly two fingerbreadths proximal from the prominent ulnar styloid bone. Insert the needle just radial to the ulna at a shallow depth of one-half inch.","Have the patient make a gentle fist, and then ask them to point their index finger straight out while keeping the other fingers curled.","If the needle is inserted too far radially, you will sample the abductor pollicis longus. If inserted too far proximally, you will end up in the overlying extensor digitorum communis.","This is usually the most distal muscle innervated by the radial nerve complex. It is your ultimate test to definitively rule in or rule out a distal radial nerve injury, such as a Posterior Interosseous Nerve entrapment at the Arcade of Frohse. It is also invaluable for demonstrating the extent of a classic 'Saturday night palsy' originating higher up at the spiral groove.","assets/images/emg/Extensor Indicus.png")
B.a77=new A.hB("First Dorsal Interosseous","Ulnar Nerve, Medial Cord, Anterior Division, Lower Trunk, C8, T1","The lateral border of the third metacarpal bone.","The medial side of the base of the proximal phalanx.","Place the hand flat on the table in full pronation, with the thumb stretched out in full radial abduction.","Pinch the meaty web space between the thumb and index finger. Insert the needle at the free edge of this web space, directing the tip back toward the proximal end of the first metacarpal bone.","Ask the patient to forcefully press their index finger laterally against your resisting finger (abduction of the index finger).","If the electrode is angled too far dorsally, you may miss the main bulk of the muscle. If angled too far volarly (toward the palm), you will mistakenly sample the opponens pollicis.","This is the holy grail for ulnar nerve testing, as it is the most distal muscle innervated by the ulnar nerve. Severe weakness here results in Froment's sign, where the patient must substitute the median-innervated flexor pollicis longus to pinch objects, causing the thumb joint to buckle. This muscle is mandatory sampling for differentiating lower cervical radiculopathies from distal ulnar entrapments at Guyon's canal.","assets/images/emg/First Dorsal Interosseous.png")
B.a79=new A.hB("Deltoid, Middle","Axillary Nerve, Posterior Cord, Posterior Division, Upper Trunk, C5, C6","The acromion of the scapula.","The deltoid tuberosity of the lateral humerus.","Have the patient lie supine or sit comfortably with their arm resting relaxed at their side.","Palpate the bony tip of the acromion and the prominent deltoid tubercle halfway down the humerus. Insert the needle exactly halfway between these two landmarks.","Instruct the patient to abduct their arm straight out to the side like an airplane wing.","Because this is a common site for routine intramuscular vaccinations, you may occasionally encounter localized, non-neuropathic muscle irritability or fibrotic scarring that can mimic disease.","The middle deltoid is a powerful abductor of the arm, but it relies heavily on the supraspinatus to securely fix the humeral head into the glenoid socket first. If the axillary nerve is damaged, often due to an anterior shoulder dislocation or a direct fracture of the surgical neck of the humerus, this muscle will show profound denervation and the patient will struggle to lift their arm.","assets/images/emg/Deltoid.png")
B.a72=new A.hB("Pronator Teres","Median Nerve, Lateral Cord, Anterior Division, Upper and Middle Trunk, C6, C7","This muscle features two distinct heads: the humeral head originates from the medial epicondyle, and the ulnar head originates from the coronoid process. The median nerve dives dangerously between them.","The lateral surface of the radial shaft, right at the midpoint.","Rest the patient's forearm on the table, fully supinated (palm up).","Draw an imaginary line connecting the medial epicondyle to the thick biceps tendon in the elbow crease. Find the midpoint of that line, move exactly two fingerbreadths distally down the forearm, and insert the needle.","Ask the patient to forcefully pronate their forearm (turn palm down) against your resistance.","If the needle electrode is pushed too deeply, it will pass right through the pronator teres and sample the deeper flexor digitorum sublimis. If inserted too far toward the ulnar side, it will hit the flexor carpi radialis.","This is the most proximal forearm muscle innervated by the median nerve. Because the median nerve must physically pierce through the two heads of this muscle to enter the forearm, it is a prime location for traumatic compression, known as Pronator Teres Syndrome. Sampling this muscle helps differentiate a high median nerve injury from a classic carpal tunnel entrapment at the wrist.","assets/images/emg/Pronator teres.png")
B.a7_=new A.hB("Triceps Brachii (Lateral Head)","Radial Nerve, Posterior Cord, Posterior Division, Middle and Lower Trunk, C6, C7, C8","The posterior surface of the humerus, situated above the radial groove.","The prominent olecranon process of the ulna at the elbow.","Have the patient rest their hand on their abdomen with the forearm pronated and the elbow comfortably flexed.","Find the midpoint between the lateral epicondyle of the elbow and the top of the shoulder. Insert the needle into the lateral aspect of the arm just below this midpoint.","Instruct the patient to extend their elbow, pushing their hand away from their body against your resistance.","As long as you strictly adhere to a lateral approach when sampling this head, you remain safely away from the major vascular bundles and nerve trunks running down the medial arm.","Of the three heads of the triceps, the lateral head is generally considered the safest and easiest to sample. It is a critical evaluation point; because the branches supplying the triceps originate very high up in the axilla, this muscle will be completely spared in a classic 'Saturday night palsy' radial nerve compression occurring lower down at the spiral groove. Its primary diagnostic utility is in isolating C7 radiculopathies.","assets/images/emg/Triceps.png")
