a=A.ce(v9,a1,s2,"INDICATED (Levels of involvement)",A.a([A.t(!1,"Typically spared as it is the first median branch",f0,k6,f0,f0,w2,h0,f0,f0,o8,f0),A.t(!0,f0,f0,h2,f0,f0,o7,h0,f0,h4,o8,f0),A.t(!0,f0,f0,h2,f0,f0,w3,w4,f0,h4,i0,f0),A.t(!0,f0,f0,h2,f0,f0,g9,h0,f0,h4,h1,f0),A.t(!1,h7,f0,f0,f0,f0,h5,h6,f0,f0,h1,f0),A.t(!1,h7,f0,f0,f0,f0,h8,h9,f0,f0,i0,f0),A.t(!1,f0,f0,f0,f0,f0,w5,f0,f0,f0,f0,f0)],n),"This case localizes the Median neuropathy to the proximal forearm. The involvement of the Palmar Cutaneous branch (causing numbness in the central palm) is a critical clinical differentiator from Carpal Tunnel Syndrome. EMG helps confirm by showing sparing of the Pronator Teres (innervated proximal to the entrapment) while potentially showing denervation in distal median or AIN muscles if the compression is significant.",a0,"pronator",a2,ae8,ae7,!0,a,A.a(["Pronator Teres Syndrome (PTS) is the second most common median nerve entrapment after CTS.","Crucial Distinction: PTS involves the Palmar Cutaneous branch, leading to sensory loss in the central palm. CTS spares this area because the branch arises proximal to the carpal tunnel.","Electrodiagnosis: The Pronator Teres (PT) is typically SPARED on EMG because the entrapment occurs as the nerve passes between the PT heads or under the FDS arch (distal to the PT branch).","NCS may show conduction slowing across the elbow, though this can be technically difficult to demonstrate compared to CTS."],af3),"Forearm Pain and Palmar Numbness")
ae7=A.cd(28,"Sudden onset of difficulty picking up small objects and an awkward tip-to-tip pinch",d5,"Noticed difficulty yesterday while knitting. She cannot properly flex the tip of her thumb or index finger. No numbness or tingling. Had deep forearm pain for 2 days preceding the weakness. No trauma or neck pain.",i4,"Knitter",i4)
ae8=A.ch("No visible atrophy (acute onset).","Mild deep tenderness in the proximal volar forearm.",v4,v3,"STRICTLY NORMAL throughout the median, ulnar, and radial distributions. No palmar or digital numbness.","Negative 'OK' sign (Patient's thumb and index finger meet in a flat 'pincer' position rather than a circle due to lack of distal IP/DIP flexion).","Right Flexor Pollicis Longus (FPL) 2/5, Flexor Digitorum Profundus (FDP) of index finger 2/5. Normal strength in Pronator Teres, FCR, and APB (Hand intrinsics). Normal strength in FDP of 4th and 5th digits (Ulnar).")
