a5=A.ce("Parsonage-Turner Syndrome",a7,s2,"INDICATED (Look for patchy denervation)",A.a([A.t(!1,h7,f0,f0,f0,f0,g9,h0,f0,f0,h1,f0),A.t(!1,h7,f0,f0,f0,f0,h5,h6,f0,f0,h1,f0),A.t(!1,h7,f0,f0,f0,f0,h8,h9,f0,f0,i0,f0),A.t(!0,f0,f0,q4,f0,f0,r7,f0,f0,h4,f0,f0),A.t(!0,f0,f0,q4,f0,f0,y3,f0,f0,h4,f0,f0),A.t(!0,f0,f0,j8,f0,f0,r9,u8,f0,h4,v2,f0),A.t(!1,f0,f0,k6,f0,f0,y4,f0,f0,f0,f0,f0)],n),"Neuralgic Amyotrophy (PTS) typically presents with a 'pain-weakness sequence': severe, deep-seated shoulder pain that lasts days to weeks, followed by patchy weakness and atrophy in the shoulder girdle. EMG confirms multifocal, patchy denervation (Fibs/PSWs) and normal paraspinals, localizing the lesion as post-ganglionic.",a6,"parsonage",a8,ae8,ae7,!0,a5,A.a(["Parsonage-Turner Syndrome (Neuralgic Amyotrophy) is an idiopathic inflammatory plexitis/neuropathy.","The hallmark is 'patchy' involvement of the brachial plexus, often affecting individual nerves (Long thoracic, Axillary, Suprascapular) rather than traditional trunks or cords.","Normal Cervical Paraspinal EMG identifies the lesion as post-ganglionic (at the plexus or nerve level), ruling out radiculopathy."],af3),"Extreme Shoulder Pain Followed by Weakness")
ae7=A.cd(34,"Tingling and burning pain on the back of the right thumb and index finger",d5,"Develop symptoms after wearing tight-fitting handcuffs during a training exercise 2 weeks ago. The pain is constant and worsened by wrist movement or wearing a tight watch. No weakness in the hand or arm. No neck pain.",i4,"Security Officer",i4)
ae8=A.ch("Mild redness over the radial aspect of the wrist. No atrophy.","Extreme tenderness over the superficial radial nerve as it emerges from under the Brachioradialis tendon (approximately 8cm proximal to the radial styloid).","2+ and symmetric throughout. Brachioradialis reflex normal.",v3,"Decreased sensation (hypesthesia) and burning (allodynia) over the dorsal first webspace and the back of the thumb.","Highly positive Tinel's sign at the radial wrist; Negative Finkelstein's test (rules out De Quervain's).","5/5 strength in ALL muscle groups including wrist/finger extension, brachioradialis, and hand intrinsics.")
a8=A.a([A.V("Wartenberg's Syndrome (Cheiralgia Paresthetica)",d9),A.V("De Quervain's Tenosynovitis","A tendonitis causing pain with thumb movement (Positive Finkelstein's), but it does NOT cause neurological numbness or an abnormal SNAP."),A.V(v8,"Radiculopathy would cause neck pain and involvement of C6 muscles (Biceps/BR) which are normal here. The SNAP is typically spared in a pre-ganglionic root lesion."),A.V("High Radial Neuropathy","A high radial lesion would cause wrist drop and weakness in the Brachioradialis, which is not present here."),A.V("First CMC Osteoarthritis","Causes joint pain and stiffness but not neurogenic tingling or sensory loss.")],ae9)
a6=A.a5(["constitutional","Negative.","musculoskeletal","Wrist/Thumb pain.","neurological","Dorsal thumb numbness. **NO WEAKNESS**."],af1,af1)
a7=A.a(["None."],af3)
a7=A.cf(A.a(["Ultrasound Wrist: Localized edema and flattening of the superficial radial nerve near the radial styloid."],af3),a7)
a9=A.a([A.ac(!0,k4,"Confirms isolated sensory radial involvement",f3,g4,l1),A.ac(!1,i7,f0,e6,i6,i8),A.ac(!1,l1,f0,f1,g1,n7)],q)
a9=A.cg(f0,A.a([A.al(!1,e8,"Normal motor function distal to the lesion",f8,v1,i8),A.al(!1,j4,f0,g6,f7,j5)],o),a9)
a6=A.ce("Wartenberg's Syndrome",a8,d4,"INDICATED (To rule out higher lesions)",A.a([A.t(!1,f0,f0,f0,f0,f0,"Extensor Indicis Proprius (EIP)",x3,f0,f0,i0,f0),A.t(!1,f0,f0,f0,f0,f0,x4,x3,f0,f0,i0,f0),A.t(!1,f0,f0,f0,f0,f0,u9,h9,f0,f0,v2,f0),A.t(!1,h7,f0,f0,f0,f0,"First Dorsal Interosseous (FDI)",h6,f0,f0,h1,f0),A.t(!1,h7,f0,f0,f0,f0,g9,h0,f0,f0,h1,f0),A.t(!1,h7,f0,f0,f0,f0,w2,h0,f0,f0,o8,f0)],n),"Wartenberg's Syndrome is a pure sensory neuropathy of the superficial radial nerve at the wrist. It is often caused by external compression (tight watches, handcuffs, casts). The hallmark is **sensory loss/pain in the snuffbox** with **strictly normal motor function**. Electrodiagnostically, the **Radial Sensory SNAP is abnormal** (low amplitude or absent) while the motor NCS and EMG are completely normal.",a7,"wartenberg",a9,ae8,ae7,!0,a6,A.a(["Wartenberg's syndrome is a pure sensory entrapment of the superficial radial nerve at the wrist.","Often confused with De Quervain's tenosynovitis; look for the neurological distribution of numbness and the abnormal SNAP to differentiate.","The hallmark is **Normal EMG** and **Abnormal Radial Sensory SNAP**.","Commonly caused by tight-fitting objects around the wrist ('Handcuff Palsy')."],af3),"Tingling on the Back of the Thumb")
ae7=A.cd(24,"Deep, poorly localized dull ache in the right shoulder and weakness when serving",i1,"Develop pain in the posterior shoulder over several months. Lately, notices he cannot 'follow through' on his serve and feels like his arm is 'giving out' during external rotation. No history of acute trauma. No neck pain or radiating numbness.",x1,"Professional Volleyball Player",i4)
ae8=A.ch("Visible wasting/atrophy of the right supraspinatus and infraspinatus fossae. Deltoid bulk is preserved.","Tenderness over the suprascapular notch (posterior scapula). No joint instability.","Symmetric 2+ throughout (Biceps, Triceps, Brachioradialis).","Full passive ROM. Pain with extreme horizontal adduction.","NORMAL throughout the arm, including the lateral shoulder (axillary patch) and all digital distributions.","Negative Empty Can test (no pain, just weakness). Negative Spurling's maneuver.","Right Shoulder Abduction (initial 15-30 degrees) 3/5. External Rotation (Infraspinatus) 2/5. Shoulder Abduction (Mid-range, Deltoid) 5/5. Biceps 5/5. Triceps 5/5.")
a9=A.a([A.V("Suprascapular Nerve Entrapment (Suprascapular Notch)",d9),A.V("Spinoglenoid Notch Entrapment","Entrapment at the spinoglenoid notch would involve ONLY the Infraspinatus, sparing the Supraspinatus. Here, both muscles are weak and atrophied."),A.V(u0,"Radiculopathy would involve the Deltoid (Axillary), Biceps (Musculocutaneous), and Rhomboids/Paraspinals. It would also often be associated with neck pain and an abnormal Biceps reflex."),A.V(y5,"Would involve a wider array of C5-C6 muscles including the Deltoid, Biceps, and Brachioradialis, and would typically have sensory loss in the lateral arm/forearm."),A.V("Parsonage-Turner Syndrome (PTS)","PTS usually presents with a hyperacute, agonizing pain followed by weakness; this case is a chronic, progressive presentation related to overhead sports.")],ae9)
a7=A.a5(["constitutional","Negative.","musculoskeletal","Deep shoulder pain.","neurological","Shoulder weakness. **NO NUMBNESS**."],af1,af1)
