c9=A.ce("Right Lower Trunk Brachial Plexopathy (Klumpke's Palsy)",d1,s2,e2,A.a([A.t(!0,f0,f0,j8,f0,f0,g9,h0,f0,h4,h1,f0),A.t(!0,f0,f0,j8,f0,f0,h5,h6,f0,h4,h1,f0),A.t(!0,f0,f0,h2,f0,f0,h8,h9,f0,h4,i0,f0),A.t(!0,f0,f0,h2,f0,f0,j9,h6,f0,h4,"C8",f0),A.t(!1,h7,f0,f0,f0,f0,r9,u8,f0,f0,v2,f0),A.t(!1,h7,f0,f0,f0,f0,r7,z2,f0,f0,"C5",f0),A.t(!1,"Confirms post-ganglionic",f0,f0,f0,f0,"C8-T1 Paraspinals",f0,f0,f0,f0,k6)],n),"Acute traction injury (upward pull) causing damage to the lower trunk (C8-T1). Localization is confirmed by: 1) Abnormal MAC and Ulnar SNAPs (post-ganglionic), 2) Weakness in all C8-T1 innervated muscles (Median, Ulnar, and Radial), and 3) Sparing of proximal (C5-C7) muscles and reflexes.",d0,"klumpke",d2,ae8,ae7,!0,c9,A.a(["Klumpke's palsy results from injury to the lower trunk (C8-T1), often due to hyperabduction of the arm.","The hallmark finding for localization is the abnormal Medial Antebrachial Cutaneous (MAC) SNAP, which distinguishes it from a C8 radiculopathy.","Physical exam classically shows a 'claw hand' due to weakness of the lumbricals and interossei.","Normal paraspinals and SNAPs would suggest a root level lesion (radiculopathy), while abnormal SNAPs and normal paraspinals confirm a plexopathy."],af3),"Weak Hand and Medial Arm Numbness")
ae7=A.cd(58,"Burning pain and numbness along the inner aspect of the right leg following knee replacement surgery",d5,"58-year-old female who underwent an uncomplicated total knee arthroplasty (TKA) 6 weeks ago. Since the surgery, she has had persistent burning pain and numbness on the medial side of her leg, extending from the knee down towards the medial ankle. No weakness noted. No back pain.","Gabapentin, Acetaminophen",z6,"Osteoarthritis of the knees")
ae8=A.ch("Well-healed surgical incision on the anterior knee. No muscle atrophy in the quadriceps.","Tenderness along the medial joint line and infrapatellar region.","2+ and symmetric patellar and Achilles reflexes.","Full ROM at the hip. Knee ROM 0-110 degrees, limited by post-surgical stiffness but not weakness.","Decreased pinprick and light touch along the medial leg below the knee (Saphenous distribution). Sensation on the thigh and lateral leg is normal.","Negative straight leg raise. Negative femoral stretch test.","5/5 strength in hip flexion (Iliopsoas), knee extension (Quadriceps), and hip adduction (Adductors).")
